<PB N="1" REF="2">
<HEAD>REASONS
AGAINST
FIGHTING:
OR,
Some Account why the Confederates
could not expect the Briti&s;h Army
&s;hould join with them whenever
they thought fit to attack the
French.</HEAD>
<P>THE Town having been mo&s;t ma|liciou&s;ly
amu&s;ed with an Account
in a Printed Po&s;t&s;cript, which, (as
it is there managed and related,) is calculated
to lay as much Reproach on the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Na|tion,
and on Her Maje&s;ty, as is po&s;&s;ible; it
cannot but be an acceptable Work to all
that have any Regard to the Honour of their
Countrey, or their Queen, to examine into
an Affair of &s;uch a Nature, and &s;tate the
&s;ame to the People, that they may not be
<PB N="2" REF="3">
impo&s;ed upon by fal&s;e Glo&s;&s;es, and malici|ous
Con&s;tructions. In our fir&s;t Entrance
into the Merits of this Cau&s;e, we &s;hall &s;ave
a great deal of Fending and Proving about
the Matter of Fact, and therefore without
enquiring into the Truth of the Relation,
which is believed to be a meer Forgery of
the <HI>Scotchman</HI> who writes that Paper,
who&s;e Talent of Lying is &s;o well known to
Mankind; yet to deal the better with him
and his Party, we will for once &s;uppo&s;e
here all his Relation to be right, and &s;hall
argue from it as if it were &s;o, (<HI>viz.) I am
no Braggadocio nor Ga&s;con, but do a&s;&s;ure you,
that I never promi&s;ed my&s;elf more from a Day
of Battle than I did from this; and I prepared
my&s;elf to fight, when&mdash;refus'd to Second
me. I ask'd him, what he did there then? He
told me, he came to fight, but that he had re|ceiv'd
Orders, which he &s;hew'd me, not to act
offen&s;ively again&s;t the Army of</HI> France.</P>
<P>Suppo&s;ing this then to be true, who are
they that make Complaint? This Author
&s;ays, <HI>many do;</HI> it is hoped it is not our good
Friends and Confederates the <HI>Dutch:</HI> Many
Rea&s;ons concur to move us to hope thus of
them: Principally that it was for &s;ome Ages
the Practice of that wi&s;e and wary People,
with us, and with all their Allies, it hath
been &s;o often, and &s;o loudly complained of
by the <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> Court in former Days, and
by their other Confederates that the <HI>Dutch</HI>
&s;ent their Deputies into the Army to con|troul
<PB N="3" REF="4">
their Generals; and &s;uch fatal Effects
have been found to be the Con&s;equence of
it, that &s;urely it can never be the <HI>Dutch</HI> that
&s;hould complain of being abandoned, but
they &s;hould look back to their former Con|duct
in the like Ca&s;es, of which the Hi&s;tory
of tho&s;e Days is full. If his Grace the Duke
of <HI>Marlborough</HI> plea&s;eth to give an Account
of the many Occa&s;ions in which this Con|duct
of the States-General hath been fatal to
King <HI>William,</HI> in his Wars in <HI>Flanders,</HI>
there will be but too many In&s;tances of the
like, more e&s;pecially beginning at the
Siege of <HI>Bonne</HI> in the Year 1674, or there|abouts.</P>
<P>If his Grace the Duke of <HI>Marlborough</HI>
doth not think fit to give his Evidence in
this Ca&s;e, the Opponents being at this Time
&s;omething Allied to his Grace's Intere&s;t,
there are not wanting living Witne&s;&s;es to
prove it, when the States Field-Deputies
refu&s;ed to let the <HI>Dutch</HI> Forces fight, as
e&s;pecially during the fir&s;t Part of the late
War, at the Bu&s;ine&s;s of <HI>Steenkirk,</HI> at <HI>Beau|mont,</HI>
before that at the long March to gain
the <HI>French</HI> Lines, when the late <HI>Dauphin</HI>
commanded the <HI>French</HI> Army; al&s;o at the
fir&s;t Siege of <HI>Mons</HI> by the <HI>French,</HI> at the
fir&s;t Siege of <HI>Namure,</HI> and many more In|&s;tances
of like Nature: It was not without
very great Difficulty that the late King
<HI>William</HI> obtain'd &s;o entire a Confidence to
be placed in him by the <HI>Dutch,</HI> as to have
<PB N="4" REF="5">
the Command of the Army compleatly in
him&s;elf. Soon as the King was dead, al|though
they have committed the Command
of their Troops to the Duke of <HI>MarlBorough,</HI>
to Prince <HI>Eugene,</HI> and the like Great Gene|rals,
yet is it plain it is all Subject, and un|der
Orders, to the Five <HI>Dutch</HI> Field-Dep$|ties,
who have their Voices in every Coun|cil
of War; and who, though they have
no Command in the Army, yet have a
Univer&s;al Command over the whole Army.
Nor can the General Act, or March, much
le&s;s Fight, if they plea&s;e to put in their Ne|gative
at a Council of War. If it is al|ledged
that they never gave their Negative
upon any probable Action, it &s;hall be an|&s;wered
in many Particulars, but not to di&s;|pute
that; it is certain they are empowered to
give a Negative mo&s;t effectually, in Ca&s;e
of which Negative the Troops would not
act, no although their General &s;hould
command them. And what &s;hall we &s;ay,
that after and notwith&s;tanding this, the
Queen &s;hould have le&s;s Authority to act than
the <HI>Dutch;</HI> that Her Maje&s;ty &s;hould not
have Power to prevent the Effu&s;ion of
Blood, when &s;he may &s;ee the Conclu&s;ion of
a Peace &s;o ea&s;ie, if the Confederates would
hear Rea&s;on; that there &s;hould be no Ne|ce&s;&s;ity
of &s;uch a Butchery, as that of <HI>Blareg|nies,</HI>
to gain perhaps the bare Retreat of the
<HI>French,</HI> and perhaps not that.</P>
<P><PB N="5" REF="6">
But to wave that Part till afterward, and
return to what was mentioned before, after
the P&mdash;of <HI>O</HI>&mdash;was come to be ad|vanced
to the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> $hrones, and by his
Succe&s;&s;es in <HI>England</HI> and <HI>$$eland</HI> had made
him&s;elf more popular in <HI>Holland</HI> than before,
the <HI>Dutch</HI> finding al&s;o that the <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> were
ill &s;atisfied with the Diffidence the States
had always &s;hewn in the Tru&s;ts of their
Army, came at la&s;t into the Mea&s;ures the
King had laid before them, and committed
their Forces to the King, with a Di&s;cretio|nary
Power to Fight, or not to Fight, when
he thought fit. It &s;hould not be forgotten
that the States were moved to this, by &s;ee|ing
the King at the Head of a Powerful
Army of his own Troops, entirely com|manding
the <HI>Imperial</HI> and <HI>Spani&s;h</HI> Armies;
and that if they &s;hould refu&s;e to give up
their Troops to him, he would be in a Con|dition
to &s;ight the <HI>French,</HI> or undertake &s;ome
Siege without their Help that their Troops
would not only lo&s;e the Honour, but the
States them&s;elves &s;hould be le&s;&s;ened in the
Figure they made in the Confederacy; that
as their Troops &s;hould perhaps be &s;carcely
in the Action, &s;o neither would their Inte|re&s;ts
be equally taken Care of in ca&s;e of any
Advantages obtained. The&s;e, and many
more, were the Arguments which really
brought in the States-General to con&s;ent to
take off their Field-Deyuties from the Ar|my,
<PB N="6" REF="7">
and leave the King entirely to act as he
&s;hould think fit.</P>
<P>Tho&s;e People who remember any Thing
of what is behind them cannot forget how
great a Point it was thought gained when
the <HI>Dutch</HI> were brought to do thus; how
the Succe&s;s, which was promi&s;ed to Affairs,
encouraged the Parliament and People to go
on more warmly in the Pro&s;ecution of the
War, becau&s;e the <HI>Dutch</HI> had now con&s;ent|ed
to take away their Re&s;traints: After the
Death of the King, as well when the Ar|mies
were commanded by Mon&s;ieur <HI>Over|kirk</HI>
as by the Duke of <HI>Marlborough</HI> him&s;elf,
the &s;aid <HI>Dutch</HI> Deputies were replaced in
their Army; on all Occa&s;ions they were ad|mitted
to &s;it in the Councils of War, and
if they did not give their A&s;&s;ent no Action
of Moment could be undertaken; farther,
the States have kept &s;uch a Negative upon
the Actions in the Field, as that even when
the Council of War have often re&s;olved on
this or that, tho&s;e Re&s;olutions have been
fir&s;t &s;ent to the <HI>Hague</HI> for the Approbation
of the States them&s;elves before they could be
put in Practice, though the Field-Deputies
have been con&s;enting to it before in the
Army. Such hath been the Power the
States-General have always re&s;erved in
their Hands to govern and re&s;train the Af|fairs
of the Army and the War, by which,
in Effect, they had the Command of the
<HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Armies and Generals; the Queen
<PB N="7" REF="8">
had the Name indeed of being at the Head
of the Confederacy, and had the Power to
put a General of Her own in the Command
over Her own Troops; but even Her Ma|je&s;ty,
and all Her Generals and Forces,
were &s;o far under the Command of the
<HI>Dutch,</HI> and &s;o far to be governed by the
Councils at the <HI>Hague,</HI> that nothing could
be done without fir&s;t applying to the &s;aid
States, or their Deputies, for their Con&s;ent:
Thus we willingly &s;ubmitted to having gi|ven
our&s;elves up to <HI>Dutch</HI> Councils, it is
not to be wonder'd that this, and more,
was &s;tooped to by &s;uch People as were come
into a State of Pupilage to the States; and
who left both the Direction of the War,
and the Management of the Peace, to them,
as if their own Nation had no Intere&s;t or
Concern in it, other than to receive their
Orders from their High Mightine&s;&s;es:
Whether it is more wonderful that any Peo|ple
&s;hould thus Sacrifice their Countries In|tere&s;t
to a Selfi&s;h Neighbour, and with a
profound and implicit Submi&s;&s;ion &s;hould
give them&s;elves over to the Management
of a Foreign Nation? Or that the &s;ame
People &s;hould now complain that Her Ma|je&s;ty
a&s;&s;umes a little Her Right of judging
when it is Right or Safe to hazard Battle,
or not, as well as the <HI>Dutch.</HI> It &s;eems to &s;ome
that the <HI>Dutch</HI> have taken this Part upon
them &s;o long, that it &s;hould now be challeng|ed
as their due; and that the Exclu&s;ion of the
<PB N="8" REF="9">
Queen of <HI>Great-Britain</HI> is mo&s;t Righteous, that
the States alone &s;hould have a Negative Voice
in the Field&punc; that the <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> Generals were
never to Fight but when the <HI>Dutch</HI> gave them
Leave, and were always to fight when they,
the <HI>Dutch,</HI> propo&s;ed it: It is counted as an
Aggravation in the pre&s;ent Ca&s;e, that Prince
<HI>Eugene</HI> was for Fighting the <HI>French,</HI> and to
Crown all, <HI>the</HI> Dutch <HI>Deputies had con&s;ented;</HI>
a Mighty Argument! What is the Infe|rence?
Then it was a mo&s;t Heinous Offence
that our General had not Orders to comply;
&s;o that the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Forces mu&s;t Bleed, and
Die, and March, and Fight, or lye Still,
ju&s;t as Prince <HI>Eugene</HI> and the <HI>Dutch</HI> Depu|ties
think fit that whenever the&s;e, for the
carrying on their Separate Views, think fit
to attack the <HI>French</HI> Army, tho' entrench'd
up to the Teeth, fortified and po&s;ted to Ad|vantage,
the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Troops, like Obedient
Slaves, mu&s;t fall on with the greate&s;t Ha|zard;
for it is well known that Her Ma|je&s;ties
Troops are never failed of the Po&s;ts
of Danger, and the Hote&s;t and mo&s;t De&s;pe|rate
of the Service. On the other Hand,
if the Advantages which offer, however
great, are accepted by the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Generals,
unle&s;s the <HI>Dutch</HI> plea&s;e to join their A&s;&s;ent:
Our Men can on no Account embrace the
Opportunity; there are Numberle&s;s Exam|ples
of this Kind to be given but we e&s;teem
it &s;o known a Truth in the Army, and eve|rywhere
el&s;e, that it is needle&s;s to mention
<PB N="9" REF="10">
any more what is &s;o Univer&s;ally known: How
then comes it to be &s;urprizing to the People
here that Her Maje&s;ty &s;hould, when &s;he &s;ees
Cau&s;e, a&s;&s;ume that Authority in the Army
which the <HI>Dutch</HI> have &s;o avowedly practi&s;ed?
And why is not Her Maje&s;ty as much of
Right empowered to do this when her own
Affairs require it, as the States-General have
been when their Affairs have likewi&s;e re|quired
it? Ob&s;erve here, the Di&s;pute in
this Part has no Relation to the Rea&s;ons
why Her Maje&s;ty declines hazarding a Bat|tle
with the <HI>French;</HI> but to the Right Her
Maje&s;ty has when Her own Affairs make it
rea&s;onable upon any Score to Fight, or not
to Fight, as She thinks fit.</P>
<P>Having thus made a Prote&s;t in Her
Maje&s;ty's Name for the Re&s;ervation to Her|&s;elf,
the guiding of Her own Affairs, it
comes in order to examine the Ca&s;e before
us, which has given &s;o great an Occa&s;ion
of Di&s;cour&s;e, <HI>viz.</HI> That the Queen has
given Orders to Her Generals not to Fight
with the <HI>French,</HI> or to undertake any Siege;
we &s;hall be wary in &s;aying that there might
be, or that there are, Rea&s;ons why it might
not be Safe for Her Maje&s;ty to hazard Her
Troops, and that there may be good
Rea&s;ons why, as Ca&s;es &s;tand, the Queen
&s;hould not venture a Battle in Conjun|ction
with the Allies, who are now in the
Field with Her: But this may be &s;aid Safely,
that whereas the Endeavours of a Party
<PB N="10" REF="11">
among us to render the Mini&s;try here, and
the Management of Affairs in the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI>
Court, &s;u&s;pected to the Allies, and that tho&s;e
wicked De&s;igns have had but too much
Succe&s;s; &s;o that great Mi&s;under&s;tandings,
&s;candalous Mi&s;repre&s;entations, and Inve|ctives,
have too much &s;upplied the Place
of the u&s;ual mutual Confidence and Affecti|on
which was formerly e&s;tabli&s;hed, and
ought now to have been cultivated between
Her <HI>Britannic</HI> Maje&s;ty and Her Allies; it
cannot be &s;uppo&s;ed that in this Ca&s;e the &s;ame
Harmony, the &s;ame Unity, the &s;ame Con|fidence,
could be between them as it were
to be wi&s;hed; and therefore while that
Confidence on both Sides hath been &s;o Art|fully
le&s;&s;ened it cannot be expected, e&s;pe|cially
by that Side, who have &s;o openly
profe&s;t their Jealou&s;ie and Di&s;&s;atisfaction,
that the other &s;hould with the like Freedom,
as on former Occa&s;ions, hazard with them
in &s;o Nice and &s;o Critical an Affair as that
of a General Battle.</P>
<P>This is not all, but it is not unknown of
what Con&s;equence the lea&s;t Blow or Di&s;ap|pointment
in Ca&s;e of Action might be to
Her Maje&s;ty's Affairs; the Party here have
not been &s;ilent in their Malicious Expecta|tions,
and have not &s;crupled to let us know
that they had &s;ome Hopes in a Di&s;appoint|ment;
they have been heard to &s;ay that
One Defeat of the Army, One Battle in the
Field, would ruin the pre&s;ent Mini&s;try, and
<PB N="11" REF="12">
fright the Queen into other Mea&s;ures: As the&s;e
are the known Hopes of this Party, and that
the Secret Corre&s;pondence between them,
and &s;ome Leading Men Abroad, who have
it much in their Power to do either Good
or Hurt in a Day of Battle, is al&s;o known,
it may not be an ill-grounded Caution, that
we &s;hould be backward to hazard a Battle
with the Enemy, while in Conjunction with
&s;ome who entertain a &s;trict Confederacy with
that Party here, who own, as above, that
their Hopes are founded upon a Suppo&s;ition
of the Army receiving a Defeat Abroad: It
is &s;ugge&s;ted that this is Suppo&s;ititious, that
no &s;uch Thoughts have been entertain'd
here, and that our Confederates are not
capable of entertaining any Thing &s;o Di&s;ho|nourable,
nor could practi&s;e the Thing
without Ruin and De&s;truction to them|&s;elves:
This may have many An&s;wers to it,
all of them &s;ignificant of the Thing, and
ju&s;tifying the Conduct of a Nation in &s;uch
a Ca&s;e. 1. That if the&s;e People here have
no &s;uch Thoughts, as perhaps &s;ome among
them may abhor &s;o wicked a Practice;
but why do they &s;peak it in their own Di&s;|cour&s;e?
Why do they plea&s;e them&s;elves
with the talking of it? Do their Tongues
&s;peak what their Hearts never thought?
It may be too true of them, that they think
little, and might talk of &s;mall matters with|out
Meaning, but Capital Mi&s;chiefs never
hang on the Tongue but when they are
<PB N="12" REF="13">
dictated from the Heart; why &s;hould they
talk thus? Would they be thought more
Wicked than they are? Or would they talk
what they did not intend, on Purpo&s;e, and
with De&s;ign, to make them&s;elves be &s;u&s;pect|ed?
Have we not heard them in the Public
Coffee-hou&s;es &s;ay on the la&s;t Proclaimed Fa&s;t
that they did not know how to keep it,
that they did not know whether they &s;hould
pray for Succe&s;s upon our Armies, yea,
or no? Or whether it were not as good that
we &s;hould be beaten Abroad, that it might
bring us to our Sen&s;es at Home; that One
Battle lo&s;t would ruin the Mini&s;try, and
blow them all up, and &s;uch Talk as this; nay,
have we not many &s;o far exa&s;perated, that
will &s;top their Ears, or &s;it down in the mid&s;t
of the Public Prayers, when the Mini&s;ter
is praying for the be&s;t of Ble&s;&s;ings upon the
Queen, and for Succe&s;s to Her Maje&s;ty's
Forces both at Sea and Land? They treat
Her Maje&s;ty with more Freedom in their
Cups, and long ago have they left off To&s;t|ing
a Health to the Generals, or Succe&s;s to
our Arms; while this Principle prevails, let
any one judge whether it is Safe for us to
venture an Engagement, tho' with an Ene|my
le&s;s Con&s;iderable, and le&s;s Dangerous,
than the <HI>French,</HI> while thus Circum|&s;tanc'd
at Home, and while the&s;e People
boa&s;t of their &s;trict Alliance, and clo&s;e
Friend&s;hip Abroad, with &s;uch People, up|on
who&s;e Conduct the Sum of Affairs very
much depends.</P>
<P><PB N="13" REF="14">
This is not to be con&s;trued as a Reflecti|on
on the Fidelity of the Allies, or a De|claration
that there is any &s;uch Thing as a
Di&s;tru&s;t on the Part of the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Court of
the Ju&s;tice or Faithfulne&s;s of the Confede|rates&punc;
but it mu&s;t be acknowledged by any
unbya$ed Judgment that the&s;e People have
done what is <HI>their po&s;&s;ible</HI> to create &s;uch a
Jealou&s;ie: After &s;uch Notices of their
Minds at Home, and Boa&s;ts of their In|fluence
Abroad, a Mini&s;try, le&s;s wary,
and le&s;s penetrating, than ours, might be well
ju&s;tified in re&s;olving to Ri&s;que nothing with
them: This is mo&s;t &s;ure, that they would
be mo&s;t inexcu&s;able, who after &s;uch Warn|ings
&s;hould venture a Thing of &s;o great a
Con&s;equence as a Battle, on a Di&s;appoint|ment
wherein they had an A&s;&s;urance that
&s;o much of the Hopes of their Enemies
did depend. Hi&s;tory might be brought to
give Evidence in this Ca&s;e, where in Affairs
le&s;s Critical than the&s;e Cautions have been
taken, and Mea&s;ures of Safety pur&s;ued, on
the lea&s;t Di&s;covery of the Secret De&s;igns of
Parties among the Confederate Troops.</P>
<P>It may be needful to &s;ay &s;omething here
to the Objection following, (<HI>viz.</HI>) that
this cannot be Rational to &s;u&s;pect, becau&s;e
it cannot be practi&s;ed but at the Ruin of
the Confederates: But many In&s;tances
have been given in the World of Armies
driven to Exigences, by being de&s;erted or
for&s;aken in the Time of Action by their
<PB N="14" REF="15">
Friends, without giving the Enemy Oppor|tunity
to break in upon the Parties who have
&s;o for &s;aken them, of any where to hurt them:
There have not wanted In&s;tances of this,
even between the &s;ame Parties we are &s;peak|ing
of, when in the Sea-fight between the
Confederate Fleet and the <HI>French</HI> Fleet, off
of <HI>Beachy-Head,</HI> in the Year 1690, when the
<HI>Dutch</HI> Admirals complained of their being
for&s;aken and betrayed by the <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> Ad|mirals,
and left to the Mercy of the <HI>French</HI>
Fleet, while the <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> made their Retreat
in the be&s;t Manner they could, that by this
