they conferr'd &s;ingly with other People&punc;
immediately the Subject of the Peace be|came
the Je&s;t of the Place: The Earl of
<HI>Strafford,</HI> the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Envoy and Plenipo|tentiary,
was Treated after a different and
uncommon Manner, and all the Councils
the Gentlemen had on that Affair di&s;cover|ed
an Inclination rather to prevent than
promote a Peace, as the propere&s;t Scheme to
