<P>But here it is fit that we ob&s;erve how
Villainous the Party Her Maje&s;ty has to
do with at Home are in their very Na|ture,
who rather than not form &s;omething
to enflame their Party, will publi&s;h &s;uch
gro&s;s Forgeries, and put Affronts of the
Gro&s;&s;e&s;t Nature upon their own Friends,
and Men of the Greate&s;t Rank in the
World: It is al&s;o the kinde&s;t and be&s;t
Con&s;truction that can be put upon this
Affair, to &s;ay that it is a Forgery of the
News-writers here, &s;et on Work by a
Party who have De&s;igns again&s;t the Queen's
Intere&s;t, and that of her Allies al&s;o; for
if it were true in Fact, if Prince <HI>Eugene</HI>
did actually Send &s;uch a Me&s;&s;age to the
Duke of <HI>Ormond,</HI> or ask him &s;uch a
Que&s;tion upon his giving his Opinion a|gain&s;t
attacking the <HI>French.</HI> is it not a
very good Rea&s;on why Her Maje&s;ty &s;hould
give &s;uch Orders? Is it not high Time
the Queen &s;hould be Mi&s;tre&s;s of Her own
Troops, and of Her own Part in the
War al&s;o? Indeed had there been no o|ther
