before, yet &s;uch a Pa&s;&s;age happening, the
<PB N="20" REF="21">
Duke of <HI>Ormond</HI> ought never to have
encamped in one Line with them after
it. This proves to any Con&s;idering Per|&s;on
to what a Degree of Subjection to our
Haughty Allies the Mini&s;try of late
Years had brought our Affairs, and how
till now we were to be called out when|ever
the Hirelings of the Foreign Prin|ces
pleas'd to demand it, and to attack
at whatever Expence of Blood, and with
whatever Di&s;advantage. Nothing can be
a greater Ju&s;tification to the Mea&s;ures now
taking than the In&s;olence of the Allies to
us, not on this Occa&s;ion only, but on
many other Occa&s;ions, and al&s;o of the
dangerous Corre&s;pondence carry'd on be|tween
&s;ome People Abroad, who&s;e Obli|gations
to Her Maje&s;ty call for other Things
from them; and a Party at Home, who
avowedly e&s;pou&s;e and ju&s;tifie the giving
us all into the Hands of the <HI>Dutch;</HI> and
that we are not to be tru&s;ted with our
own Peace, but ought to take it at a Se|cond
Hand, as the <HI>Dutch</HI> plea&s;e to make
it for us. Will any contend that we
&s;hould not now open our Eyes, and that
we &s;hould not now act by our own Coun|cils?
Will they &s;till &s;uppo&s;e us in our
Non-age and Pupil-age, that we mu&s;t be
led about Blindfold, and be made Tools
and Engines to the <HI>Dutch</HI> Avarice and
<HI>Imperial</HI> Ambition? The Party here, to
cover the Eyes of their Followers, have
<PB N="21" REF="22">
now taken a New Cour&s;e in this Matter,
to &s;ti$le ad Compiain$s again&s;t our Allies,
and to make is Obvious &s;o much as to
compla$$ of the <HI>Dutch,</HI> or of the harde&s;t
and mo&s;t unju&s;t Treatment from them,
or from any other of the Allies; they
are Indu&s;trious to &s;pread Reports that
Her Maje&s;ty &s;eeks Occa&s;ions again&s;t the
<HI>Dutch,</HI> and that we are all driving into
a War with the <HI>Dutch,</HI> as if we could be
in no Alliance with them, but &s;uch
a one in which they mu&s;t be allowed to
give the Law to our Conduct, and make
their Markets of us, by putting the mo&s;t
Shameful Tricks upon us, and managing
us to gain on their Crutches, or rather
carry them on our Shoulders; this has
been no New Practice; &s;ome Men had
Eyes to &s;ee it before, tho' now 'tis con|fe&s;t
it becomes more undeniably Public
by their own U&s;age of the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Nation,
according to the following Lines out of
a Ballad of their own making, at the
Treaty of <HI>Nimeguen,</HI> when the <HI>Dutch</HI>
played as many fal&s;e Cards as they have
done now.</P>
<LG>
<L>The Whigs lately put out the Nation to Nur&s;e,</L>
<L>With an Old Wooden Leg and a Crutch,</L>
<L>And to teach us to Go, ty'd our <HI>Leading-&s;trings</HI> too,</L>
<L>And gave them to hold to the <HI>Dutch.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="22" REF="23">
<L>The <HI>Dutch,</HI> as who would not, that under&s;tood
