<L>Brought us up heavy Burthens to $word$;</L>
<L>And as we grew weak, they doubled our Pack,</L>
<L>And laid on the Weight of the War.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Like <HI>I&s;achar</HI>'s A&s;s, we couch'd to the Load,</L>
<L>And carry'd our Burthen &s;o true;</L>
<L>The <HI>Dutch</HI> tho't we had been &s;o beat to the <HI>Road,</HI></L>
<L>We &s;hould be their <HI>Pack-Hor&s;e</HI> quite thro',</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>But &s;ome Ages of Light have clear'd up our Sight,</L>
<L>And now from our Tutelage breaking,</L>
<L>We think we're at Age for our&s;elves to engage,</L>
<L>And the <HI>Peace</HI> may be of our own making.</L>
</LG>
<P>This is the true State of the <HI>Dutch</HI> Ma$nagement,
which many People, who for$merly
were hard to believe, are now for$ward
to inform them&s;elves of; for the Sak$of
the&s;e it may be very fit to have the tru$
Source of the pre&s;ent Ca&s;e laid open, an$
when the Plot is more fully di&s;covered, $word$
Knavery of the Parties will be more eviden$
for it is not hard to per&s;wade any one$
believe that all this S$r is not made witho$$
&s;ome beginning, and without many pre$ous
Intrigues and $aballings of the Pa$
here with their Friends at the <HI>Hague&punc;</HI> a$
this brings us back to the Treaty of Pea$
and the Conduct of the Party in <HI>Engla$$</HI>
It is mentioned above how when the Im$riali&s;ts
<PB N="23" REF="24">
found a Treaty of Peace unavoida|ble,
and that Her <HI>Britannic</HI> Maje&s;ty pre&s;t
it &s;o earne&s;tly, that it would go on without
them, if they did not think fit to come in;
they at la&s;t complied, and how, after their
having &s;o complied their Application,
turn'd immediately to counter-act the Pro|gre&s;s
of the Treaty, that &s;o, tho' they could
not interrupt the beginning, they might
di&s;appoint the end of a Treaty, and bring
on the War by the nece&s;&s;ary Con&s;equence;
what were the Mea&s;ures they took to bring
this to pa&s;s is obvious to every ordinary
View; and how far they obtain'd their
End, as they thought, is evident al&s;o; the
Armies being already in the Field, while
the Negotiations at <HI>&V;trecht</HI> were at a full
&s;tand, by the in&s;i&s;ting upon An&s;wers in
writing from the <HI>French</HI> Plenipotentiaries,
in&s;tead of entring into a Treaty by Confe|rence,
as was fir&s;t intended; during the
whole Negotiation at <HI>&V;trecht,</HI> the Parties
in <HI>England</HI> and in <HI>Holland</HI> &s;pread about Re|ports,
and po&s;itively affirmed, that the <HI>Bri|ti&s;h</HI>
Court had made a Separate Peace with
<HI>France;</HI> and even the <HI>Memorials</HI> from &s;ome
of the Foreign Mini&s;ters &s;ignified as much;
the Party from hence a&s;&s;ur'd them Abroad
&s;o con&s;tantly of it, that all Means po&s;&s;ible
were made u&s;e of to put a Stop to the Ne|gotiations,
that they might bring the <HI>Bri|ti&s;h</HI>
Mini&s;ters Abroad to declare them&s;elves;
but they were too penetrating for the other
<PB N="24" REF="25">
to break into their Councils, till the other
thought of this Experiment, which, as a
Great Man among the Party here &s;aid,
could not fail, and this was their la&s;t Re&s;ort,
<HI>viz.</HI> that the Armies &s;hould join, and that
a Motion &s;hould be made, whatever the Po|&s;ture
of Affairs might be, to attack the
<HI>French</HI> Army in their Camp, and force them
to a Battle; then, &s;aid they, you produce
the de&s;ired Effect, let it fail either Way;
for if the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> General Fights, we &s;hall
either Conquer or be Defeated, if we Con|quer
the Treaty of Peace is at End, if we
are Defeated the Mini&s;try in <HI>England</HI> are
Ruined, and &s;o we &s;hall Conquer that
Way. On the other Hand, if the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI>
General will not Fight then they di&s;cover
them&s;elves that they have made a Se|parate
Peace; that the&s;e have been the
Methods of the Party, and the Steps they
have taken, they may deny if they think
fit; but the publi&s;hing them here will &s;erve
to convince them that their Mea&s;ures are
not quite &s;o Impenetrable, or their private
Re&s;olves &s;o well Concerted and Concealed,
as they &s;latter them&s;elves to believe.</P>
<P>Now it may appear al&s;o, that altho' the&s;e
Things promi&s;ed a &s;ure Event equal to the
Expectation of the Contrivers, yet their Po|liticks
have failed at this Time, the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI>
Councils have thought fit to countermine all
this Plot; Fir&s;t, they have not been &s;o
<HI>Dupe</HI> as to be drawn into the Snare of Fight|ing,
<PB N="25" REF="26">
and engage the Enemy with a Confe|deracy,
who had &s;ome Views which made
it le&s;s E&s;&s;entaial than at another Time,
whether they were Victors, or not: Here
the Match was not equal; for the Victory
only was the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> General's Safety, the
only Security of his Mi&s;tre&s;s, the Queen,
and of the whole Nation&punc; whereas a Defeat,
however fatal to us, was not entirely with|out
&s;ome Pro&s;pects that render'd it le&s;s
fatal in its Con&s;equences to &s;ome People than
at other Times; for, fay the&s;e Men, one
Blow would Ruin all the New Scheme, and
Re&s;tore Affairs, &s;et up the Old Mini&s;try
again, and break all the Mea&s;ures of the
<HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Court. This is the Foundation up|on
which, as is &s;aid, &s;ome were &s;o open to
&s;ay, &startq;They knew not how to keep the Fa&s;t
that was appointed by Her Maje&s;ty for the
Succe&s;s of the War, for they did not know
whether they had be&s;t pray for Victory or
no;&endq; nay, a known Citizen of <HI>London,</HI>
who&s;e Name is no Secret, was plea&s;ed to &s;ay
openly, &startq;He did not know but that if we
were a little beaten it might be for our Good
at this Time;&endq; let any one that knows and
&s;ees the&s;e Things, judge Impartially, whe|ther,
while &s;uch a Temper is reigning a|mong
us, it would con&s;i&s;t with the Wi&s;dom
and Penetration of Her Maje&s;ty and Her
Council to venture a Battle, either as joined
with &s;uch Allies Abroad, or &s;urrounded
with &s;uch Private Enemies at Home, but by
<PB N="26" REF="27">
the Wi&s;dom of the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Councils we have
countermined this Plot; and now they find
them&s;elves all di&s;appointed, for they can
neither bring the Army to run Headlong
into an Engagement, nor have they yet
made them&s;elves Ma&s;ters of our Mea&s;ures;
this Wi&s;dom however they have learn$d by
it, <HI>viz.</HI> that the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Affairs are no
more in Foreign Management; that if
they will end the War Honourably, and
make a Firm, La&s;ting, Peace, they may
have the Concurrence of the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Court
for the Advantage of all their Intere&s;ts,
and for the procuring to them a Ju&s;t and
Rea&s;onable Satisfaction; but that the <HI>Bri|ti&s;h</HI>
Nation are not to be Bullied into the
War, as another &s;aid the Emperor would
not be Bullied into the Peace.</P>
<P>There are the true Plans of this Affair,
and now it &s;eems as if they are come to
&s;uch a Head, that they mu&s;t be brought
to an I&s;&s;ue one Way or other; the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI>
Court have de&s;ired a Fair Treaty, that an
Honourable Peace might be obtained for
all Parties&punc; the Ob&s;tinacy of a few encou|couraged
from hence, and prompted at
<HI>Vienna,</HI> have done their utmo&s;t to prevent
that Peace being General; and as if they had
in&s;ulted our Court upon it, they had brought
it to this Point, which was &s;poken openly at
the <HI>Hague;</HI> &startq;We will take Care they &s;hall
not make a General Peace, and let them
make a Separate Peace if they dare: If they
<PB N="27" REF="28">
have now pu&s;h'd on that Notion &s;o far as
they can, &s;hould <HI>Great-Britain</HI> make &s;uch a
Peace as Her own Safety requires, they
may &s;ee Cau&s;e to blame them&s;elves; for
tho' the Queen of <HI>Great-Britain</HI> has been
very far from de&s;iring to make Her own
Peace exclu&s;ive from Her Allies, yet no
good Subject of Her Maje&s;ty can patiently
hear the Tools of the pre&s;ent Parties, or
the Emi&s;&s;aries of tho&s;e who oppo&s;e this
Peace, in&s;ult Her as being afraid to &s;e|cure
Her&s;elf and Her own People: If a Sepa|rate
Peace &s;hall be the Re&s;ult of the Ob&s;ti|nacy
of tho&s;e who&s;e Intere&s;ts are made
wilfully to oppo&s;e Her Maje&s;ty, the Con&s;e|quences
lye at their Door; Her Maje&s;ty is
not to be in&s;ulted by Prince <HI>Eugen$,</HI> or any
one el&s;e, as if She was afraid to pur&s;ue Her
own Mea&s;ures, or afraid to own what She
has propo&s;ed: The Intrigue is of Nece&s;&s;ity
to be now made Publick, the Mea&s;ures
taken on both Sides will now appear, yea,
they do appear: The Plot is again&s;t a Peace;
not again&s;t this or that Condition of
Peace, but again&s;t Peace in General; the
Tran&s;action is double, let us &s;ee the dark
Sides of both.</P>
<P>The Emperor is po&s;itive again&s;t a Peace,
his Rea&s;on is plain and undeniable; his is
the Gain of the War; all that hath been
fought for, or all that is contended for in
the War, or in the Peace, is for him: While
the Contention is carrying on, what is it he
<PB N="28" REF="29">
po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es? He receives the whole Revenues of
the Electorate of <HI>Bavaria,</HI> and of the Dutchy
of <HI>Mantua,</HI> the large Contributions levyed
upon the State of <HI>Genoa,</HI> the Grand Duke
of <HI>Tu&s;cany,</HI> many of the Territories of
the Pope, the State of <HI>Venice,</HI> and the other
Princes of <HI>Italy,</HI> this he puts into the Impe|rial
Trea&s;ury for the Support of $his War,
whil&s;t yet it is depending; and all this is,
be&s;ides the Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of &s;uch Parts of the
<HI>Spani&s;h</HI> Monarchy as are obtaind for him,
with the Blood, and at the Expence, of the
Confederates; &s;uch are the Provinces of the
<HI>Low Countries,</HI> the Rich Dutchy of <HI>Milan,</HI> the
Kingdom of <HI>Naples,</HI> the Principality of <HI>Cata|lognia,
&amp;c.</HI> except only the Expence of the Em|peror
in gaining and maintaining the Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;i|on
of the la&s;t of the&s;e Places. Two Things will
appear eviden tin this, in which the true Rea|&s;on
of the Emperors de&s;iring the Continuance
